**RoomIBot**

This problem explores a simple &quot;robot,&quot; named &quot;RoomIBot,&quot; whose goal is to completely traverse its environment. RoomIBot starts at a random location in a room -- you don&#39;t have control over RoomIBot&#39;s initial location. The walls of the room are blue; RoomIBot is green, and the empty area is white. Each time RoomIBot takes a step, it leaves a grey trail behind it. When RoomIBot has completely explored its environment, it stops automatically.

**Surroundings**

Not surprisingly, RoomIBot has limited sensing power. It can only sense its surroundings immediately to the north, east, west, and south of it. For example,

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the above image, RoomIBot sees a wall to the north and west and it sees nothing to the east or south. This set of surroundings would be represented as follows:

NxWx

The four squares surrounding RoomIBot are always considered in NEWS order: an x represents empty space, the appropriate direction letter (N, E, W, and S) represents a wall blocking that direction. Here are all of the possible RoomIBot surroundings:

**State**

RoomIBot&#39;s memory is also limited. In fact, it has only a single value from 0 to 99 available to it. This number is called RoomIBot&#39;s **state**. In general, &quot;state&quot; refers to the relevant context in which computation takes place. Here, you might think of each &quot;state&quot; as one piece -- or behavior -- that the robot uses to achieve its overall goal. RoomIBot always begins in state 0. The **state** and the **surroundings** are all the information that RoomIBot has available to make its decisions!

**Rules**

RoomIBot moves according to a set of rules of the form:

StateNow Surroundings -\&gt; MoveDirection NewState

For example,

0 xxxS -\&gt; N 0

is a rule that says &quot;if RoomIBot is in state 0 and sees the surroundings xxxS (there is nothing to the North, East, or West, but a wall to the South), it should move North and stay in state 0.&quot;

The MoveDirection can be N, E, W, S, or X, representing the direction to move or, in the case of X, the choice not to move at all.

If this were RoomIBot&#39;s only rule and if RoomIBot began (in state 0) at the bottom of an empty room, it would move up (north) one square and stay in state 0. However, **RoomIBot would not move any further** , because its surroundings would have changed to xxxx, which does not match the rule above.

**Wildcards**

The asterisk \* can be used inside surroundings to mean &quot;I don&#39;t care whether there is a wall or not in that position.&quot; For example, xE\*\* means &quot;there is no wall North, there is a wall to the East, and there may or may not be a wall to the West or South.&quot;

As an example, the rule

0 x\*\*\* -\&gt; N 0

is a rule that says &quot;if RoomIBot is in state 0 and sees **any surroundings without a wall to the North** , it should move North and stay in state 0.&quot;

If this new version (with wildcard asterisks) were RoomIBot&#39;s only rule and if RoomIBot began (in state 0) at the bottom of an empty room, it would first see surroundings xxxS. These match the above rule, so RoomIBot would move North and stay in state 0. Then, its surroundings would be xxxx. These **also** match the above rule, so RoomIBot would again move North and stay in state 0. In fact, this process would continue until it hit the &quot;top&quot; of the room, when the surroundings Nxxx no longer match the above rule.



**Comments**

Anything after the pound sign (#) on a line is a comment. Comments are human-readable explanations of what is going on, but ignored by RoomIBot. Blank lines are ignored as well.



**An example**

Consider the following set of rules:

# state 0 goes N as far as possible

0 x\*\*\* -\&gt; N 0 # if there&#39;s nothing to the N, go N

0 N\*\*\* -\&gt; X 1 # if N is blocked, switch to state 1

# state 1 goes S as far as possible

1 \*\*\*x -\&gt; S 1 # if there&#39;s nothing to the S, go S

1 \*\*\*S -\&gt; X 0 # otherwise, switch to state 0

Recall that RoomIBot always starts in state 0. RoomIBot now consults the rules from top to bottom until it finds the first rule that applies. It uses that rule to make its move and enter its next state. It then starts all over again, looking at the rules and finding the first one from the top that applies.

In this case, RoomIBot will follow the first rule, repeatedly, up to the &quot;top&quot; of its environment, moving north and staying in state 0 the whole time. Eventually, it encounters a wall to its north. At this point, the topmost rule no longer applies. However, the next rule &quot;0 N\*\*\* -\&gt; X 1&quot; does apply now! So, RoomIBot uses this rule which causes it to stay put (due to the &quot;X&quot;) and **switch to state 1**. Now that it is in state 1, neither of the first two rules will apply. RoomIBot follows state 1&#39;s rules, which, when used repeatedly, guide it back to the &quot;bottom&quot; of its environment. And so it continues... .



**Getting familiar with RoomIBot**

Open the Chrome browser. Do not use any other type of browser.

Navigate to http://learn.cs.uml.edu/ext/RoomIBot where you will find your RoomIBot work area. The following instructions will help you get familiar with manipulating your RoomIBot.

- Press **Go** to watch what the default rules tell RoomIBot to do
- Press **Stop** to stop RoomIBot from moving
- Press **Step** to see RoomIBot make one move
  - Notice that as you step, the values shown in the yellow area change. Those values tell you:
    - Your current state. In the default rule set, state 0 moves RoomIBot North until reaching a wall, at which time it switches to state 1. State 1 moves RoomIBot South, until reaching a wall, at which time it switches back to state 0.
    - Your surroundings. If you are not next to a wall, your surroundings will be xxxx. If you are next to the East wall, your surroundings will be xExx to indicate that there is a wall to the East, but no wall to the North, West, or South. If you are in the Northeast corner, your surroundings will be NExx, to indicate that there are walls to RoomIBot&#39;s North and East but not to its West or South.
    - Cells to Go. This indicates how many places within the room it has not yet reached.
    - Previous Rule. This is rule that was just acted upon (commonly referred to as &quot;just executed&quot;).
    - Next Rule. This is the rule that is about to be executed, as determined by the current state and surroundings.
- Press **Step** a number of times, and watch the Previous Rule and Next Rule. As you continue to press **Step** and RoomIBot reaches a wall, you will notice that the Surroundings change from xxxx to Nxxx or xxxS, to indicate that RoomIBot is adjacent to the North or South wall.







Important Note: As you work on the following problem, use the technique described above to step through your rule set. Watch the Previous Rule, Next Rule and Surroundings, and compare the Next Rule with the rule that you &quot;expect&quot; to be used given those Surroundings. With practice, you will find that you are able to quickly identify problems with your rule set (and later, with other programs you write) by comparing what you&#39;re shown actually happening against what you &quot;expect&quot; to happen.



**Your task**

Write a set of RoomIBot rules that will allow RoomIBot to begin at any location in an empty room, and cover (move through) the entire room.

 Devise a strategy. If you are finding that it requires many rules to accomplish this, you may want to rethink your strategy. It can be accomplished in as few as 7 or 8 rules.

 Remember to click on the &quot;Enter rules for RoomIBot&quot; before you try to run RoomIBot.

 Remember that your solutions must work from arbitrary starting positions within the environment. When your rule set seems to work, use RoomIBot&#39;s Reset and Go buttons, or the teleport buttons, to test your rule set many times. Be comfortable that it will work correctly given any starting position, including in the middle, at any edge, or at any corner. Once you happy with your solution, submit your solution at **https://tinyurl.com/y5zmcly6**



If you are intrigued and would like a bit more challenge: Click on the arrows next to the word &quot;Map&quot; in the RoomIBot work area. This will move you to a new &quot;map&quot; (room) that has walls within the room in addition to the surrounding walls. There are a number of maps available. Write a set of RoomIBot rules that will allow RoomIBot to completely navigate a some of these more sophisticated maps. The maze map is an interesting one to try.
